column11: The Virginia gubernatorial race will take place on 7 November 2017. The campaign has drawn national attention and money, with both Democrats and Republicans viewing the contest as a referendum on President Trump (The Washington Post, The Washington Post, The Hill). Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help.

It's coming down to voter turnout now. Northam has led or tied in every poll since July, and two of the September polls put his margin at more than 5%. But, even though the most recent Wason Center poll gives Northam a 6% margin (albeit with a 3.7% margin of error at the 95% confidence level), their assistant director sounded a cautionary note in characterizing the results:

https://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2017/governor/va/virginia_governor_gillespie_vs_northam-6197.html Used the above list of polls to ground my estimates. Popularity of a party a year after winning a presidential election is bound to fall, especially given that Trump is the president, but Right wing tend to be less vocal in polls (and clearly more likely to vote Republican than popularity figures would suggest) and turn out in greater numbers in state elections. This balances out to give Republicans a slight edge above their performance as forecasted by the polls.

September polls are all over the place, from a tie (Suffolk) to a less than 5% Northam victory (Mason-Dixon and FOX News) to a greater than 10% Northam victory (Quinnipiac). https://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2017/governor/va/virginia_governor_gillespie_vs_northam-6197.html#polls Treating Quinnipiac as an outlier - which has been true all along, I give heavy weight to the central tendency for a Northam victory with a less than 5% margin. But, with margins of error in the 4% range or greater, both adjacent possibilities (Northam greater than 5% and Gillespie less than 5%) are plausible outcomes. The possibility of systematically correlated polling errors makes me most uncomfortable in the direction of a Gillespie victory, so I'm giving that bin a substantially higher weight than the Northam greater than 5% bin.

ADVANTAGE DEMOCRATS. Not by force effort mind you. but rather by default as establishment Republicans continue to take the wind out of conservative hopes. In 2017, the first state legislative seat to switch from Democrat to Republican as a result of a special election was the District 42 seat of the Louisiana House of Representatives. The first state legislative seat to switch from Republican to Democrat as a result of a special election was Carroll 6 of the New Hampshire House of Representatives. Democrats flipped another Republican seat in District 9 of the New York State Assembly District 9. On July 11, Democratic candidates in Oklahoma won election to Senate District 44 and House District 75, flipping those seats from Republican control to Democratic control. On September 12, Democrats flipped the Belknap 9 district in the New Hampshire House of Representatives. Democrats flipped a second seat on September 12 in District 46 of the Oklahoma House of Representatives.

This forecast represents a composite of several different ways of looking at the election. In brief, I think both candidates have a hardcore base that would vote for them regardless of any normal developments that may occur between now and election day. I think that hardcore base is slightly smaller for Northam than for Gillespie. However, I think Northam benefits from Trump's politics, which will energize his base and dampen Gillespie's base. Among swing voters, I think Northam benefits from being more well-known than Gillespie, and benefits from being associated with the outgoing Terry McAulliffe, and therefore appeals to voters that want to preserve the status quo.

No new polls since my last forecast, but upon careful consideration, I've shifted my Northam forecast more heavily to a 5% or less margin. Unless I see a significant uptick in Northam's polling margins, I'm going to stick with the sense that this is a very tight race.
